---
import { getPageContract } from '../config/site'
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'

const page = getPageContract('about')
---

<BaseLayout description={page.description} pageTitle={page.title} path={page.path}>
  <article class="about">
    <h1>About</h1>

    <p>
      I'm Stephen Sawyer. I build self-hostable systems software -- the kind of tools
      that run on your hardware, store data you can actually inspect, and don't phone
      home.
    </p>

    <p>
      Most of my work is in <strong>Python</strong>, <strong>Go</strong>, and
      <strong>Rust</strong>. Browser-facing surfaces use <strong>TypeScript</strong>,
      <strong>Bun</strong>, and <strong>Astro</strong>, with <strong>Vue</strong> only
      when an interaction actually earns client-side state. I reach for
      <strong>PostgreSQL</strong> by default and use <strong>SQLite</strong> when the
      product is intentionally local-first.
    </p>

    <h2>What I care about</h2>

    <p>
      <strong>Ownership.</strong> If you can't run it yourself, you don't own it.
      Every product I build is designed to run on a single machine under your control.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Boring infrastructure.</strong> Novel architecture is a liability until
      proven otherwise. I want the system that wakes nobody up at 3am, not the one
      that looks impressive on a whiteboard.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>The data layer is the truth layer.</strong> Relational data, explicit
      schema, query paths you can inspect. If you can't trace a value through the
      system, it's too clever.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Shipping beats planning.</strong> A working system you iterate on
      outranks a perfect design doc. Complexity must be earned -- every abstraction
      needs justification beyond "might be useful someday."
    </p>

    <h2>The stack</h2>

    <p>
      Python for backends, automation, and operational tools. Go for services,
      daemons, CLIs, and networking-heavy work. Rust for native runtimes,
      auditable boundary work, capture paths, custody code, and shared-core systems
      tools.
    </p>

    <p>
      On the browser side: Astro-first pages with Vue kept to island-sized,
      justified interactions. No SPA shell, no analytics junk, no gratuitous
      hydration. If an interaction ever earns extra client-side behavior, it needs
      to justify itself.
    </p>

    <p>
      This site runs on that exact stack -- Astro static output on Bun, hand-written
      CSS, and Caddy in front of a boring Docker container.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
